postcontent:
COLT SINGLE ACTION FRONTIER SCOUT 22LR. F SERIES. SERIAL NUMBER DATES IT TO 1959.  Here's a post from a Colt Forum describing the gun:
'The Frontier Scouts with the K serial numbered had zinc alloy frames, grip frames and loading gates which were much heavier than the aluminum ones. The K guns were bright nickel plated, available in .22 LR, .22 Magnum and .22 CAL (shipped with .22 LR and .22 Magnum cylinders) and had 4 3/4 inch (Frontier Scout) or 9 1/2 inch (Buntline Scout) barrels. They were introduced in 1960 and were made until about 1970. Many K Scouts were sold as "sets" of guns, sets being pairs of Frontier Scouts or Buntline Scouts or combination sets consisting of one Frontier Scout and one Buntline Scout.
In high condition, they are all desirable guns, but there were more of the K numbers Scouts produced than the Q numbered Scouts.'

title: For Sale/Trade:  Free Professional Gun Cleaning
postcontent:
I am offering a free professional cleaning for your semi-auto pistol, revolver, shotgun or rifle.  

Now that I have your attention.  I am learning the gunsmith trade and, in return, you would allow me to keep your gun overnight or a few days to study.  You tell me when you want your gun returned.  I will provide you a receipt proving ownership of the gun.

The service would include:

- complete disassembly
- thorough cleaning and detailed inspection of parts for wear and function
- complete reassembly and function check

I will NOT:

- Make ANY modifications or repairs to your gun.  If I find parts that are worn or broken I will make recommendations for repair/replacement.
- Take your gun to the shooting range.  It will remain locked in my safe until it is returned to your hands.

I don't use ultrasonic cleaners or any other processes that have the potential to damage your gun.

Thanks for your time, and I hope you choose to take advantage of this free service.

postcontent:
This is what I know about the gun. Its an original 1943 Remington-Rand M 1911 A1 US Army Issue. (Only a few blood spots) According to the serial number this gun was shipped in April of 1943. It is stamped with "FJA" inspector's mark. FJA are the initials of Frank J. Atwood, inspector of ordnance. The "P" proof mark is located near the magazine release and on top of the slide, in front of the rear sight. Cross cannons ordnance mark on the right rear of the frame, to the right of the hammer pin. "UNITED STATES PROPERTY" over the serial number with "M1911A1 U.S. ARMY" to the right of the slide stop pin. Also has the G marking on top of the frame next to the disconnector and P proof mark on top of the slide, in front of the rear sight. HS marked barrel. HS is the marking of High Standard.

This gun is all original, and a wartime piece, as you can tell by the blood spots on the slide and grip. It also comes with original U.S. marked Military issued Holster. This gun still functions perfect, and feeds regular hard ball ammo without fail. A great collector piece for any WWII collection.

title: For Sale/Trade:  1942 Colt M1911 A1 National Match
postcontent:
RARE 1942 Colt M1911 A1 national match pistol. This is what I know about the gun. Its an original 1942 Colt M 1911 A1 US Army Issue. (matching numbers except slide does not show serial number behind hammer) According to the serial number this gun was shipped in May of 1942. It is stamped with WB inside a Box for Colonel Waldemar S. Broberg, Hartford/Springfield Ordnance District, Army Inspector of Ordnance: July 1, 1941 - June 16, 1942. The WB inspected pistols are a little more rare for that time frame.

Not sure how this gun made it back to the states, but it appears the gun was made into a national match pistol during the 1950's or early 1960's, it does not have "NM" stamped on the slide.. But not all pistols back then were stamped with "NM" for national match. There are two types of Camp Perry National Match pistols.. The kind sent back to Armories and stamped SA for Springfield Armory and NM for Colt Armory. These were tuned, and fitted by the armory for military camp perry match shooting. The second was private gunsmiths these were done in competition with the armories for the same reason. Many prominent Gunsmiths of the time wanted national match recognition and made their own finally tuned pistols. It appears this one might have been done by the military, as the barrel has been re-stamped. This gun is in its original time frame finish (parkerized). All Proof markings to fit era. Bore is excellent and looks shinning.

This pistol is a shooter. It is amazingly tight and special fitted for accuracy. Its an amazing piece of history and looks beautiful as well. Definitely a one of a kind 1911. Would be a prize piece for any collection.

I have many pictures if you want more. FTF in tulsa area only.. All reasonable offers considered. Email if interested. Will trade multiple guns.. Please list your offer and values of guns. email or text 918-four02-zero854.

title: Want To Buy:  CZ 27
postcontent:
I would like to buy a CZ 27 with Czech markings. 

There were generally 3 types of markings that can be found on these pistols: 

1) Czech markings (as shown in the picture) which generally were made post-WWII, but some pre-war pistols may have survived the Nazi occupation without being re-marked. In the picture you can see that the left side of the slide looks very different from the Nazi marked ones (see #2 below). Additionally, the serial number is listed on both the slide and frame on the right side rather than on the left side like the Nazi ones. The year of manufacture on these ones can be found on the left side of the frame, in the case of the picture below, it is the "47" marking for 1947.

2) Nazi markings from both pre-war models that were re-stamped by the nazis as well as models made during the Nazi occupation. These pistols generally say "Pistole Modell 27   Kal. 7,65" on the left side of the slid, and they have the serial number listed on the left side of the frame. I do NOT want this type.

3) Neither Czech nor Nazi marked. These were produced immediately after the Nazi occupation from parts that were left over that had not yet been stamped with Nazi markings. I would accept this type.

Let me know if you have one to sell or trade.

Thanks

Beware of a guy who has a Hellpup ak pistol listed for sale. He wanted to trade the Hellpup for one of my gun, I agreed(before knowing this). He would email me like once a day, he makes up excuses as to why he can't get back to you any quicker. So I set a meet place/time/location and a day before we met he comes up with more excuses as to why he wants to reschedule. So we reschedule all over again, A couple days go by and he emails me again(like 4 days to be exact) he tells me he wants meet that week that only now he wants me to come to HIS area, now from here is when I started to see something was fishy about this guy, so I call off the deal because I've never dealt with anyone who acted as shady as bro did. So come to find out I'm doing a little research on the hellpups when out of nowhere I see the EXACT SAME pictures he has on his listing, off the bat I knew this guy is either trying to rob some hard working mans money or is trying to rob us for our guns. title: For Sale:  NEW KEL-TEC KSG
postcontent: The KSG (Kel-Tec Shotgun) is Kel-Tec CNC’s first entry into the shotgun market. The size, shape, and design is similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward. The KSG weighs 6.9 lbs. and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1” overall length and an 18.5” cylinder bore barrel. Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 12 rounds of 12 gauge 3” rounds in total (6 per tube). It can also reliably shoot shells as short as 1 3/4" up to the 3". This simple and reliable pump action feeds from either the left or right tube. The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard. The pump includes an under picatinny rail for the mounting of a forward grip, a light, or a laser. The included top picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights. Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included. The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil. The KSG receiver is made from hardened steel and includes the magazine tubes which have been welded in place. The grip and stock assembly is made of glass reinforced nylon (Zytel) and is easily disassembled by pushing out 2 pins, which store in 2 holes in the grip when removed. The barrel and pump assembly is removed by loosening the 2 front magazine tube nuts with a coin and sliding the assembly forward.
